Factor Analysis

Adapted from Ewart Thomas’s “Factor Analysis and Cluster Analysis”

Introduction

This tutorial covers factor analysis with R. For the related Psych 253 lecture slides, click here. In factor analysis, our various observed variables are caused by latent factors; the observed variables that are caused by the same latent factor should cohere with one another, or “hang together”.

In class and in HW3, we use an example data set from Bertram Malle, a former Psych 253 student! Malle collected data on participants’ self-ratings on 32 personality traits, ‘distant’, ‘talkative’, ‘easygoing’, etc., and was interested in how we represent the “self”. It’s pretty unlikely there are actually 32 different dimensions of personality; rather people probably vary along a small number of dimensions and that it is this low-dimensional variation that generates the observed pattern of variation and covariation among the 32 traits (or variables).

Factor Analysis is a method (not unlike SEM) for analyzing the covariation among the observed variables to address the questions:

  1. How many latent factors are needed to account for most of the variation among the observed variables?
  2. Which variables appear to define each factor; hence what labels should we give to these factors? If the observed covariation can be explained by a small number of factors (e.g., 2-5), this would increase our understanding of the relationships among the traits or variables!

For a more in depth mathematical explanation of factor analysis, check out the lecture notes from Stanford’s CS 229 Machine Learning class taught by Andrew Ng. For more math on PCA, check out these notes. For a great conceptual explanation of PCA and eigenvalues/vectors check out this tutorial.

Define some terms

Before we get started with factor analysis, let’s define some terms:

  • Factor: An underlying or latent construct that ‘causes’ the observed variables, to a greater or lesser extent. Algebraically, a factor is estimated by a linear combination of observed variables. When the ‘best fitting’ factors are found, it should be remembered that these factors are not unique; it can be shown that any rotation of the best-fitting factors is also best-fitting. We use the criterion of ‘interpretability’ to select the ‘best’ rotation among the equally ‘good’ rotations: To be useful, factors should be interpretable. Rotation of factors is used to improve the interpretability of factors.
  • Factor loadings: The degree to which the variable is driven or ‘caused’ by the factor; akin to the size of the ‘path coefficient’ in a causal diagram, Factor –> Variable. The loadings are uiui and vivi in Xi=uiF1+viF2+eiXi=uiF1+viF2+ei
  • Communality of a variable: The extent to which the variability across subjects in a variable is ‘explained’ by the set of factors extracted in the factor analysis. Uniqueness is just 1-Communality.
  • Variance accounted for by a factor: The amount of common variance for a set of observed variables that is explained by the factor. The 1st factor extracted in most methods explains more variance than the remaining factors.
  • Factor score coefficients/Factor weights: Since a factor is defined as a linear combination of observed variables, F=ΣwiXiF=ΣwiXi. The set of weights, wiwi, for each factor gives the factor score coefficients for that factor.
  • Factor score of a person Let xijxij be the score of person jj on variable ii. Then Fj=ΣwixijFj=Σwixij is the factor score for person jj on factor FF. It can be seen that a person’s factor score is a specific linear combination of that person’s observed scores on all variables.
  • Eigenvalue: The kkth eigenvalue is equal to the variance accounted for by the kkth most important factor. They are used to compute the % variance accounted for by a factor, and the cumulative % variance accounted for by the the first nn factors.
  • Interpretation & Rotation of Factors: Perhaps the most exciting part of exploratory factor analysis is the choice of theoretically interesting labels for the extracted factors. This is done, in part, but noting which variables have ‘high’ loadings on a factor, and noting also the sign of these loadings. Often, the unrotated factors (usually the principal components; PCs) are more difficult to interpret than the rotated factors. That is, rotation is a technique that is used to improve the interpretability of factors. Note that:
    • The definition and interpretation of principal components (PC’s) is not affected by how many PC’s are extracted
    • If mm PC’s are extracted and these mm PC’s are then rotated to define mm rotated factors, the mm rotated factors explain exactly the same amount of variance as do the mm PC’s
    • The interpretation of, say, the 1st rotated factor might depend on how many factors are extracted.

Factor Analysis with R

Now, let’s try using factor analysis with Malle’s dataset! We start by standardizing the variables:

d_stan = as.data.frame(scale(d))

By default the function factanal() will rotate the factors using varimax rotation (rotation = 'varimax'). Let’s start by just looking at the unrotated factors. Here, we’re doing maximum likelihood (ML) estimation, assuming that our observed variables (e.g., XiXi) come from a mixture of several Gaussian distributions (i.e., each latent variable is from a unique Gaussian distribution with some noise). Our goal is to figure out which variables “belong” to which distribution/latent factor.

### Factor analysis with no rotation
res1b = factanal(d_stan, factors = 10, rotation = "none", na.action = na.omit)

First, we can look at the sums of squared (SS) loadings; these are the eigenvalues, or the variance in all variables which is accounted for by that factor (i.e., the eigenvalue/# of variables = proportion variance). If a factor has a “high” SS loading/eigenvalue, then it is helping to explain the variances in the variables. In the factanal() output, the factors are ordered by their eigenvalues, with higher eigenvalues first. As a rule-of-thumb a factor is important if its eigenvalue is greater than 1 (i.e., the average); this is also referred to as the Kaiser Rule. Here, factors 1-6 appear to be important.

Compute eigenvalues from factor loadings

Let’s try computing the eigenvalue of the first factor using the factor loadings, and then estimate the proportion variance explained by this factor!

# Compute eigenvalue of factor 1
loadings_fac1 = res1b$loadings[,1]
eigenv_fac1 = sum(loadings_fac1^2); eigenv_fac1
## [1] 6.706
# Compute proportion variance
eigenv_fac1/32
## [1] 0.2096

Uniqueness & Communality

We can also look at the uniqueness of each variable. Uniqueness =1−=1− Communality, where Communality is SS factor loadings for all factors for a given variable. If all the factors jointly explain a large percent of variance in a given variable, that variable has high Communality (and thus low uniqueness). Let’s look at the **uniqueness of the variables, and then try to calculate uniqueness for the variable distant by ourselves!

res1b$uniquenesses
## distant talkatv carelss hardwrk anxious agreebl   tense    kind opposng 
##  0.4155  0.3662  0.4333  0.3766  0.3414  0.1086  0.2480  0.4474  0.4136 
## relaxed disorgn outgoin approvn     shy discipl   harsh persevr friendl 
##  0.4137  0.1677  0.2036  0.6425  0.3228  0.4614  0.3813  0.4951  0.3363 
## worryin respnsi contrar sociabl    lazy coopera   quiet organiz criticl 
##  0.3481  0.3921  0.4166  0.3575  0.4101  0.5047  0.2855  0.2315  0.5505 
##     lax laidbck withdrw givinup easygon 
##  0.6612  0.0050  0.2171  0.4644  0.5503
# Calculate uniqueness
loadings_distant = res1b$loadings[1,]
communality_distant = sum(loadings_distant^2); communality_distant
## [1] 0.5845
uniqueness_distant = 1-communality_distant; uniqueness_distant
## [1] 0.4155

Visualize Loadings

To get a sense for the different factors, it can be helpful to visualize the variables in 2D space, such as plotting Factor 1 against Factor 2.

### Plot loadings against one another
load = res1b$loadings[,1:2]
plot(load, type="n") # set up plot 
text(load,labels=names(d_stan),cex=.7) # add variable names

Can you make sense of these factors? It can be difficult to label factors when they are unrotated, since a description of one factor might overlap with a description of another factor. For instance, we we could define Factor 1 as talkative & organized vs. quiet & disorganized, but Factor 2 could be defined as talkative & disorganized vs. organized and quiet – this doesn’t make much sense! However, let’s see what happens when we rotate the factors. Note that when the “best-fitting” factors are found, these factors are not unique. Any rotation of the best-fittng factors is also best-fitting.

Rotation of Factors

There are many methods we can use to rotate the factors, but the method called varimax rotation is the most common, and thus the default in R’s factanal(). Varimax rotation essentially orthogonally rotates the factor axes with the goal of maximizing the variance of the squared loadings of a factor on all the variables in the factor matrix. In other words, varimax rotation looks for a rotation (i.e., a linear combination) of the original factors that maximizes the variance of the loadings (i.e., maximizing variance=Σ(l2i,f−mean(l2))variance=Σ(li,f2−mean(l2)), where l2i,fli,f2 is the squared loadings of the iith variable on the ffth factor, and mean(l2)mean(l2) is the mean of the squared loadings). As a result, each variable tends to load more heavily on a single factor (and load very little on other factors), making the interpretation of a factor easier.

### Factor analysis with rotation
res1a = factanal(d_stan, factors = 10, rotation = "varimax", na.action = na.omit)
res1a$loadings

Here we can see that now variables like sociabl and shy load heavily on Factor 1, but have very low loadings on Factor 2. As a result, we can define or label Factor 1 using these terms (e.g., extraverted vs. introverted), and then define Factor 2 using terms that load heavily on Factor 2 but less so on Factor 1 (e.g., Factor 2 might be conscientiousness, i.e., hardwrk vs. lazy).

Creating composite variables

Spurious factors are introduced if (a) the XiXi have overlapping items, or (b) some XiXi are functions of other XjXj (e.g.,X3=X2−X1X3=X2−X1). On a related note, redundant or synonymous variables hinder the extraction of general factors. If possible, try to combine synonomous variables into composites.

First, we might want to see how many factors we can extract from smaller sets of data. For instance, if we reduce our dataset down to p=5 variables, we can’t pull out k=10 factors as we did above! In order to extract k factors we need more datapoints (p) than independent parameters, i.e., (p−k)2>p+k(p−k)2>p+k.

k = 2
p = 5

yes = 'yes! lets extract k factors!'
no = 'no! we need more data or fewer factors!'

ifelse(((p-k)^2 > p+k), yes, no)
## [1] "yes! lets extract k factors!"

Let’s try combining some synonyms and then look at the extracted Factors!

shy = rowMeans(cbind(d_stan$distant, d_stan$shy, d_stan$withdrw, d_stan$quiet))
outgoing = rowMeans(cbind(d_stan$talkatv, d_stan$outgoin, d_stan$sociabl))
hardworking = rowMeans(cbind(d_stan$hardwrk, d_stan$persevr, d_stan$discipl))
friendly = rowMeans(cbind(d_stan$friendl, d_stan$kind, d_stan$coopera, d_stan$agreebl, d_stan$approvn, 
    d_stan$sociabl))
anxious = rowMeans(cbind(d_stan$tense, d_stan$anxious, d_stan$worryin))
#etc, you guys choose what you want to combine
combined_data = cbind(shy,outgoing,hardworking,friendly,anxious)
combined_data = as.data.frame(combined_data)
res2 = factanal(combined_data, factors = 2, na.action=na.omit)
res2$loadings
